Recover Debian on microSD (StarFive) without reflashing
This guide fixes a common boot failure where the kernel cannot find the root filesystem due to mismatched device naming (e.g., mmcblk0p4 vs mmcblk1p4). The robust solution is to use a UUID (or PARTUUID) for the root partition so booting works regardless of how the kernel enumerates devices.
You already confirmed the filesystems are clean and your boot partition contains kernel, initrd, DTBs, and extlinux config.

Prerequisites
    • Another Linux machine (your laptop) with an SD card reader.
    • Your microSD inserted and showing as e.g. /dev/sda with:
        ◦ /dev/sda3 → boot (FAT)
        ◦ /dev/sda4 → root (ext4)
    • Basic terminal tools: lsblk, blkid, mount, sed, nano.
On the board (StarFive / SBC), the SD card may appear as /dev/mmcblk0pX or /dev/mmcblk1pX. This inconsistency is the root cause of the boot error.

Step 0 — Verify filesystem health
sudo fsck -y /dev/sda3   # FAT boot
sudo fsck -y /dev/sda4   # ext4 root
Expect clean or repaired without fatal errors.

Step 1 — Mount the boot partition and inspect config
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/bootpart
sudo mount /dev/sda3 /mnt/bootpart
ls -l /mnt/bootpart/extlinux
cat /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf
You should see entries like:
linux /vmlinuz-5.15.0-starfive
initrd /initrd.img-5.15.0-starfive
fdtdir /dtbs
append root=/dev/mmcblk1p4 rw console=tty0 console=ttyS0,115200 earlycon rootwait ...

Step 2 — Get the UUID of the root partition
On your laptop, run:
sudo blkid /dev/sda4
Sample output:
/dev/sda4: UUID="11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555" TYPE="ext4"
Copy the UUID string.

Step 3 — Update extlinux.conf to use UUID
    1. Backup the config:
sudo cp /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf.bak
    2. Edit the file:
sudo nano /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf
    3. Change lines like:
append root=/dev/mmcblk1p4 rw console=tty0 console=ttyS0,115200 earlycon rootwait ...
to:
append root=UUID=11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555 rw console=tty0 console=ttyS0,115200 earlycon rootwait ...
    4. Do the same change for the rescue entry.
    5. Save (Ctrl+O, Enter), exit (Ctrl+X).
    6. Unmount:
sudo umount /mnt/bootpart
    7. Reinsert into the board and boot.
Now the kernel will always find the correct partition by UUID, regardless of mmcblk0 or mmcblk1 naming.

Step 4 — Post‑boot hardening (once the system boots)
When you’re in Debian on the board:
# Ensure initramfs and boot menu are in sync
sudo apt update
sudo apt install --reinstall u-boot-menu
sudo u-boot-update   # regenerates /extlinux/extlinux.conf

# Ensure kernel + initramfs are current
sudo update-initramfs -u -k all

# Verify extlinux.conf still uses UUID
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf
If u-boot-update overwrites the config with /dev/mmcblk*, set the UUID permanently in /etc/default/u-boot or /etc/default/u-boot-menu:
U_BOOT_ROOT="UUID=11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555"
Then run:
sudo u-boot-update

Troubleshooting tips
    • Error: VFS: Cannot open root device → UUID is wrong or mistyped.
    • Error: Waiting for root device UUID=... → initramfs missing UUID support (rare in Debian). Rebuild initramfs with update-initramfs -u.
    • Revert quickly:
sudo mount /dev/sda3 /mnt/bootpart
sudo cp /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf.bak /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf
sudo umount /mnt/bootpart
    • Card hardware issues? Clone with ddrescue before further edits:
sudo ddrescue -f -n /dev/sda sdcard.img sdrescue.log

Appendix — Useful one‑liners
Print only the critical lines from extlinux.conf:
grep -E '^(default|menu|label|linux|initrd|fdtdir|append)' /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf
Get just the UUID of /dev/sda4:
sudo blkid -s UUID -o value /dev/sda4
Replace old root= with UUID automatically:
UUID=$(sudo blkid -s UUID -o value /dev/sda4)
sudo sed -i.bak "s#root=/dev/mmcblk[0-9]p4#root=UUID=${UUID}#g" /mnt/bootpart/extlinux/extlinux.conf

Outcome
After replacing root=/dev/mmcblkXp4 with root=UUID=..., the board will boot correctly without worrying about mmcblk0 vs mmcblk1 differences, and no reflash is needed.
